<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Biology" id="306" name="Anatomy of Flowering Plants">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Group of cells having common origin and performing same function are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Tissue</option><option id="B">Organ</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Basic building unit of organs.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Tissues whose cells are capable of division are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Meristematic tissues</option><option id="B">Permanent tissues</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Greek: meristos = divided.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Meristems that occur at tips of roots and shoots are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Apical meristems</option><option id="B">Lateral meristems</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Responsible for primary growth (increase in length).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Meristem occurring between mature tissues and helping in grass regeneration after grazing is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Intercalary meristem</option><option id="B">Apical meristem</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>A type of primary meristem.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Tissues that do not divide further and have attained a definite form are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Permanent tissues</option><option id="B">Meristematic</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Simple or Complex.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Permanent tissue having only one type of cells is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Simple tissue</option><option id="B">Complex tissue</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Parenchyma, Collenchyma, Sclerenchyma.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Major simple tissue forming bulk of plant organs with thin cellulose walls is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Parenchyma</option><option id="B">Sclerenchyma</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cells can be takes many shapes, often isodiametric.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Living simple tissue that provides mechanical support to growing parts like petiole? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Collenchyma</option><option id="B">Parenchyma</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cells have thickened corners (cellulose, hemicellulose, pectin).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dead simple tissue with thick lignified walls for mechanical support is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sclerenchyma</option><option id="B">Collenchyma</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Includes fibres and sclereids.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Tissues made of more than one type of cells working as a unit are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Complex tissues</option><option id="B">Simple tissues</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Xylem and Phloem.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Conducting tissue for water and minerals from roots to stem? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Xylem</option><option id="B">Phloem</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also provides mechanical strength.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Four components of Xylem are tracheids, vessels, xylem fibres and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Xylem parenchyma</option><option id="B">Sieve tubes</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Parenchyma is the only living component.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Conducting tissue for food materials from leaves to other parts? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Phloem</option><option id="B">Xylem</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Bi-directional transport.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Main conducting elements of phloem in angiosperms are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sieve tube elements</option><option id="B">Vessels</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Associated with companion cells.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cells that regulate pressure gradient in sieve tubes are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Companion cells</option><option id="B">Phloem fibres</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specialized parenchymatous cells.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Outermost layer of primary plant body is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Epidermis</option><option id="B">Endodermis</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Usually single layered.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Waxy thick layer on epidermis to prevent water loss is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cuticle</option><option id="B">Suberin</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Absent in roots.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Small pores in epidermis of leaves for gas exchange are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Stomata</option><option id="B">Lenticels</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Enclosed by guard cells.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In grasses, guard cells are ____-shaped.</text>
            <option id="A">Dumb-bell</option><option id="B">Bean</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Usually they are bean-shaped in dicots.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Epidermal hairs on stem are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Trichomes</option><option id="B">Root hairs</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Multicellular, help in reducing transpiration.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Central part of stem/root containing pith, pericycle, etc. inside endodermis is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Stele</option><option id="B">Cortex</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Consists of all tissues inner to endodermis.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Tissue system between epidermis and vascular bundles is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ground tissue system</option><option id="B">Epidermal</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Consists of cortex, pericycle, pith and medullary rays.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In dicot stem, vascular bundles are arranged in a ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ring</option><option id="B">Scattered</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic feature of dicots.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In monocot stem, vascular bundles are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Scattered</option><option id="B">Ring-like</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Surrounded by sclerenchymatous bundle sheath.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Increase in girth of plant due to lateral meristems is ____ growth.</text>
            <option id="A">Secondary</option><option id="B">Primary</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Result of vascular cambium and cork cambium.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Tissue responsible for secondary growth in dicots is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cambium</option><option id="B">Epidermis</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Present between xylem and phloem (Intrafascicular).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Outer protective tissue that replaces epidermis during secondary growth is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Periderm (Cork)</option><option id="B">Endodermis</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forms bark.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Common name of Phellem is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cork</option><option id="B">Sieve tube</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Impervious to water due to suberin.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Common name of Phellogen is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cork cambium</option><option id="B">Vascular cambium</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produces phellem outwards and phelloderm inwards.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Common name of Phelloderm is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Secondary cortex</option><option id="B">Inner bark</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Parenchymatous cells.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lens-shaped openings for gas exchange in bark of woody trees? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lenticels</option><option id="B">Stomata</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formed by phellogen.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary xylem and primary phloem in root are arranged on ____ radii.</text>
            <option id="A">Alternate (Radial)</option><option id="B">Same (Conjoint)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard root vascular arrangement.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Protoxylem towards periphery and metaxylem towards center is ____ condition.</text>
            <option id="A">Exarch</option><option id="B">Endarch</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found in roots.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Protoxylem towards center and metaxylem towards periphery is ____ condition.</text>
            <option id="A">Endarch</option><option id="B">Exarch</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found in stems.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Vascular bundle with xylem and phloem on same radius is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Conjoint</option><option id="B">Radial</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found in stems and leaves.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Presence of cambium between xylem and phloem makes bundle ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Open</option><option id="B">Closed</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Capable of secondary growth.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Absence of cambium in vascular bundle makes it ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Closed</option><option id="B">Open</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secondary growth not possible (Monocots).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Endodermis cells in root with suberin thickenings are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Casparian strips</option><option id="B">Velamen</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Blocks apoplastic water movement.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Innermost layer of cortex is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Endodermis</option><option id="B">Epidermis</option><option id="C">Pericycle</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gateway for water into xylem.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dicot leaf is also called ____ leaf.</text>
            <option id="A">Dorsiventral</option><option id="B">Isobilateral</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Anatomically different upper and lower surfaces.</explanation>
        </question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Phloem cells that lack nucleus at maturity are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sieve tube elements</option><option id="B">Companion cells</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cytoplasm is peripheral.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary meristem that appears later in life and helps in secondary growth? No, that's lateral. Primary is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Apical and Intercalary</option><option id="B">Cork cambium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contribute to primary plant body.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Secondary meristems are ____ in origin.</text>
            <option id="A">Lateral (Fascicular, Interfascicular, Cork cambium)</option><option id="B">Apical</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Develop after primary growth.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Wood is common name for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Secondary xylem</option><option id="B">Secondary phloem</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Bulk of the trunk in trees.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lightly colored, functional outer part of wood for water transport is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sapwood</option><option id="B">Heartwood</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also called Alburnum.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dark, hard, central part of wood with tannins and resins is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Heartwood</option><option id="B">Sapwood</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also called Duramen; resistant to insects.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In temperate regions, cambium is very active in spring, producing ____ wood.</text>
            <option id="A">Spring / Early</option><option id="B">Autumn / Late</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Larger vessels with wider cavities.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>One set of spring and autumn wood appears as ____ ring.</text>
            <option id="A">Annual / Growth</option><option id="B">Periderm</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used to estimate age of tree (Dendrochronology).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Large, colorless, empty cells in grass leaves for leaf rolling are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Bulliform cells</option><option id="B">Guard cells</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reduce water loss by making leaf flaccid.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Monocot leaf is also called ____ leaf.</text>
            <option id="A">Isobilateral</option><option id="B">Dorsiventral</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Similar upper and lower surfaces; stomata on both sides.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Mesophyll of dicot leaf is differentiated into ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Palisade / Spongy parenchyma</option><option id="B">Xylem / Phloem</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Palisade is towards upper epidermis.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Mesophyll of monocot leaf is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Not differentiated</option><option id="B">Differentiated</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Only spongy-like parenchyma with few air spaces.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lateral roots and vascular cambium during secondary growth originate from ____ in roots.</text>
            <option id="A">Pericycle</option><option id="B">Cortex</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Layer inner to endodermis.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Vascular bundle in monocot stem is ____ (size detail).</text>
            <option id="A">Peripheral ones are smaller than central ones</option><option id="B">All same</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic distribution pattern.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hydathodes help in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Guttation (Exudation of water drops)</option><option id="B">Transpiration</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Located at tips or margins of leaves.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Sclereids are found in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Fruit walls of nut, pulp of Pear, Guava</option><option id="B">Leaves only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Provide grittiness to fruits.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element of xylem is characteristic of Gymnosperms?</text>
            <option id="A">Tracheids only (no vessels in most)</option><option id="B">Vessels</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lack true vessels found in angiosperms (except Gnetales).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element of phloem is found in Gymnosperms instead of sieve tubes?</text>
            <option id="A">Sieve cells / Albuminous cells</option><option id="B">Companion cells</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Simpler conducting system.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Starch sheath in dicot stem refers to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Endodermis</option><option id="B">Cambium</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cells are rich in starch grains.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary xylem in mature plants formed first is ____, later is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Protoxylem / Metaxylem</option><option id="B">Meta / Proto</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reflects developmental stages.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ray parenchyma cells form ____ ray in secondary growth.</text>
            <option id="A">Vascular / Medullary</option><option id="B">Primary</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Radially conduct water and food.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Endodermis of monocot root has how many vascular bundles? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">More than 6 (Polyarch)</option><option id="B">2 - 4 (Diarch-Tetrarch)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dicot roots usually have fewer bundles.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Soft wood refers to wood of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Gymnosperms (non-porous, lack vessels)</option><option id="B">Angiosperms</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hard wood (porous) find in angiosperms.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Bark includes all tissues outside ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Vascular cambium</option><option id="B">Cork cambium</option><option id="C">Endodermis</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Includes periderm and secondary phloem.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Bast fibres is another name for ____ fibres.</text>
            <option id="A">Phloem</option><option id="B">Xylem</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Obtained from plants like Hemp, Jute, Flax.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lenticels are formed due to ____ activity.</text>
            <option id="A">Phellogen (Cork cambium)</option><option id="B">Vascular cambium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Local destruction of phellem.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Balloon-like outgrowths of xylem parenchyma into vessel lumen? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Tyloses</option><option id="B">Gums</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Block water conduct in heartwood.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Vessels are dead at maturity? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (lignified walls, no protoplasm)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Efficient for water flow.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Gymnosperms do not show annual rings? No, they do in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Temperate regions</option><option id="B">Tropical areas</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Annual rings require seasonal variation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary meristem responsible for forming ground tissue: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ground meristem</option><option id="B">Protoderm</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Part of apical meristem differentiation.</explanation>
        </question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Histogen theory: ground tissue is formed by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Periblem</option><option id="B">Plerome</option><option id="C">Dermatogen</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hanstein's theory: Dermatogen->Epidermis, Plerome->Stele.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Tunica-Corpus theory proposed by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Schmidt</option><option id="B">Haberlandt</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tunica gives rise to outer layers; Corpus to inner core.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Quiescent center in root apex has ____ mitotic activity.</text>
            <option id="A">Low / zero</option><option id="B">Very high</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reserve center for regeneration.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cystoliths are crystals of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Calcium carbonate</option><option id="B">Calcium oxalate (Raphides)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found in leaves of Banyan/Rubber plant.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Velamen is a specialized tissue in roots of ____ plants.</text>
            <option id="A">Epiphytic (Orchids)</option><option id="B">Hydrophytic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Absorbs moisture from atmosphere.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Water-containing and air-containing cavities in monocot vascular bundles? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Protoxylem lacuna / Schizogenous cavity</option><option id="B">Pith</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formed by disintegration of protoxylem.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Vascular cambium in dicot root is entirely ____ in origin.</text>
            <option id="A">Secondary</option><option id="B">Primary</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forms from pericycle and conjunctive tissue post-primary growth.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Aerenchyma is found in plants in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Freshwater (Aquatic)</option><option id="B">Desert</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Provides buoyancy and gas exchange.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lateral roots are ____ in origin.</text>
            <option id="A">Endogenous (Pericycle)</option><option id="B">Exogenous</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Grow from inner layers of parent root.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Axillary buds are ____ in origin.</text>
            <option id="A">Exogenous (Surface layers)</option><option id="B">Endogenous</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Grow from superficial tissues of stem.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cambium present between xylem and phloem within same bundle? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Intrafascicular cambium</option><option id="B">Interfascicular</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Primary origin.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cambium formed between two vascular bundles? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Interfascicular cambium</option><option id="B">Intrafascicular</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secondary origin from medullary ray cells.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Kranz anatomy is seen in leaves of ____ plants.</text>
            <option id="A">C4 (Maize, Sugarcane)</option><option id="B">C3</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Large bundle sheath cells with chloroplasts.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hydathodes are also called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Water stomata</option><option id="B">Lenticels</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Operate under high root pressure.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Pith is large and well-developed in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dicot stem / Monocot root</option><option id="B">Dicot root</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dicot roots often have very small or no pith.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Pericycle of dicot stem is in form of ____ patches.</text>
            <option id="A">Sclerenchymatous / Semilunar</option><option id="B">Continuous ring</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found above phloem patches (Hard Bast).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Intercalary meristem contributes to ____ growth.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary</option><option id="B">Secondary</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increases length of internodes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Presence of lignin in cell walls is characteristic of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sclerenchyma / Vessels / Tracheids</option><option id="B">Parenchyma</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Provides rigidity and strength.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Pits in cell walls allow ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lateral transport between cells</option><option id="B">Nothing</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Thickened areas have thin regions for diffusion.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Gymnosperms lack companion cells; they have ____ cells.</text>
            <option id="A">Albuminous (Strasburger)</option><option id="B">Sieve</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Perform similar regulatory roles.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which phloem element is first to be lost in woody stems?</text>
            <option id="A">Phloem parenchyma</option><option id="B">Sieve tubes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to growth of secondary phloem.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Late wood vs Early wood: Late wood has ____ vessels.</text>
            <option id="A">Narrower</option><option id="B">Wider</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formed later in the season.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dendroclimatology uses annual rings to study ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Past climates / weather patterns</option><option id="B">Rainfall only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Width of ring reflects favorability of year.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Pericycle in dicot root gives rise to ____? No, lateral roots.</text>
            <option id="A">Lateral roots and vascular cambium parts</option><option id="B">Cortex</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Maintains meristematic potential.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Monocot stems lack ____?</text>
            <option id="A">Cortex and Pith differentiation</option><option id="B">Phloem</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ground tissue is broadly uniform.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Suberization makes cell wall ____ to water.</text>
            <option id="A">Impermeable</option><option id="B">Permeable</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Safety barrier in endodermis and cork.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Casparian strips are found on ____ and ____ walls of endodermis.</text>
            <option id="A">Radial / Tangential</option><option id="B">Outer surface only</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forces symplastic route.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Plant with most complex anatomy? No. ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Angiosperm trees</option><option id="B">Grasses</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reflected in growth and tissue variety.</explanation>
        </question>
